  The economic returns of industrial enterprises improved. 
In 1993, the composite efficiency index of all the province's 
industrial enterprises was 96.4 percent, an increase of 10.4 
percentage points from the previous year. The production and 
sales rate of industrial products was 97.5 percent, an increase 
of 1.9 percentage points. The profit/tax rate on capital was 
9.8 percent, increasing by 0.5 percentage points. The profit 
rate on cost was 4.4 percent, increasing by 0.7 percentage 
points. The turnover of circulation capital was 1.57 times, 
0.02 times more than the previous year; and the overall labor 
productivity, in terms of value added, was 11,546 yuan per 
person. However, the rate of value growth slowed down. 
Economic returns did not rise evenly among enterprises: Large 
profit/tax increases for a few handsome profit earners such as 
the metallurgical and building industries disguised the poor 
economic returns in other enterprises. 
  The construction industry, pulled by rapid increases in 
investment in fixed assets, developed rapidly. The growth value 
for the construction industry in 1993 was 9.045 billion yuan, up 
16.6 percent over the previous year. Overall labor productivity 
was 7,409 yuan per person, up 7.2 percent. New progress was 
also made in design and works technology in the sector. 
  Geological prospecting also made new progress. In 1993, 
mechanized rock core drilling across the province covered 
239,500 meters of land, the province discovered 10 new mineral 
deposits, and increased reserves were reported for seven 
minerals. Prospecting of coal, bauxite, other nonferrous and 
ferrous metals showed larger reserves. 
<H5>  III. Investment in Fixed Assets </H5>
  Investment of fixed assets registered high growth. The total 
fixed-asset investment in 1993 for the province was 43.1 billion 
yuan, up 35.3 percent from the previous year, for real growth of 
9.6 percent in actual work amount [as published] after deducting 
price rises. Of this total, that made by state-owned units was 
28.305 billion yuan, up 49.6 percent; of which 15.151 billion 
yuan was in capital construction, up 50 percent; 8.532 billion 
yuan in technological innovation and transformation, up 45.7 
percent; and 2.168 billion yuan in commercial housing, up 147 
percent. The investment made by collective units was 7.571 
billion yuan, up 59 percent; and that by individuals was 7.256 
billion yuan, down 11.6 percent. Of the investment made by 
state-owned units, 10.345 billion yuan was in central projects, 
up 26.2 percent over the previous year, while 17.96 billion yuan 
was in local projects, up 67.5 percent. 
  The investment structure improved further, and 
infrastructure 
facilities and infrastructure industry were boosted. Of the 
total investment made by state-owned units in 1993, the 
investment in primary industry was 1.477 billion yuan, up 40.5 
percent over the previous year; that in the secondary industry 
was 16.084 billion yuan, up 27.8 percent; and 10.744 billion 
yuan was in tertiary industry, up 129.5 percent. Education and 
health obtained 912 million yuan in investment, up 49 percent. 
  Key investment projects moved faster. 5.846 billion yuan 
worth of investment was made in the 54 large and medium-sized 
capital construction and transformation projects the went beyond 
the fund ceilings, which was 96.9 percent of the annual planned 
amount. Eleven key projects, such as the Zhengzhou Thermal Power 
Plant, Luoyang Petroleum Chemicals Plant, No. 6 Mine of the 
Pingdingshan Mineral Bureau, Sanmenxia Huanghe Bridge, and 
Queshan Cement Plant, were built and put into operation or 
underwent testing, injecting new vitality into the province's 
economic development. 
  The increase in fixed-asset investment for the whole 
province 
in 1993 amounted to 18 billion yuan. The main figures for newly 
increased production capacity are as follows: 2.29 million 
tonnes of coal mining, 670,000 tonnes of natural gas and oil 
extraction, 510,000 kw of the installed capacity of generating 
units, 2.38 tonnes of cement in various grades, 2.87 million 
standard-weight boxes of plate glass, 117 km of 110,000-volt or 
above power lines, and 1,529 km of standard grade 4 highways as 
recognized by the Ministry of Construction. 
<H5>  IV. Transport, Post, and Telecommunications </H5>
  The province's transport industry transported 472,994,800 
tonnes of cargo in 1993, up 7.5 percent over the previous year; 
and 612,398,100 passengers, up 5.4 percent. Income for the 
province's transport sectors earned from transport services 
continued to rise. But transport modes remained uncoordinated 
and transport "bottlenecks" were an outstanding problem. 


