  Post and telecommunications service were further 
strengthened. The total turnover of posts and telecommunications 
service province-wide was 1.222 yuan, up 51.5 percent over the 
previous year. By the end of 1993, there were 478,900 city 
telephone accounts, an increase of 176,000 over the previous 
year. The proportion of program-controlled telephones increased 
to 80 percent of total city telephone capacity. Seventy-six 
counties (cities) have hooked into domestic and international 
program exchange networks. Paging and mobile phones have 
increased in number rapidly. 
<H5>  V. Domestic Trade </H5>
  Stocks and supplies for the consumer goods market were 
plentiful. Commodity supply continued to be bigger than demand. 
The total commodity retail volume of the whole province was 
61.636 billion yuan, up 21.3 percent over the previous year (or 
a real growth of 11.9 percent allowing for price rises). Of 
this total, the retail volume of consumer goods was 51.733 
billion yuan, up 24.8 percent; and that of agricultural 
production goods was 9.903 billion yuan, up 5.9 percent. Of 
this consumer goods retail volume, 45.455 billion yuan were 
sales made to residents, up 22.6 percent over the previous year; 
and 6.278 billion yuan to corporate bodies, up 43 percent. 
  Purchases and sales on urban markets were brisk and the 
recovery of rural markets was rapid. The total retail sales of 
consumer goods of the whole province in 1993 was 25.423 billion 
yuan, up 29.1 percent over the previous year. The total retail 
sales of consumer goods of all counties and places below the 
county level was 26.31 billion yuan, up 20.9 percent, and was 
6.8 percentage points faster than the previous year in growth 
rate. Viewed in terms of economic sectors, the retail volume of 
state-owned enterprises was 25.687 billion yuan, up 18 percent 
from the previous year; that of collective enterprises was 
18.619 billion yuan, up 22.7 percent, up 22.7 percent; and that 
of all other sectors was 13.316 billion yuan, up 26.9 percent. 
The retail volume of farming population vis-a-vis the 
nonfarming population grew 19 percent. 
  Of major commodities, the retail volume of food products 
grew 
steadily, with a 17.4 percent, 3.4 percent, and 3.6 percent 
increase over the previous year respectively for eggs, pork, and 
aquatic products. The sales volumes of consumer goods such as 
garment, color televisions, cameras, and washing machines 
continued to rise. 
  Markets for factory goods stabilized following vibrant 
activity. The total purchase by material supply and marketing 
units of the whole province was 27.048 billion yuan, up 30.1 
percent from the previous year; the total sold was 28.472 
billion yuan, up 28.1 percent. Of the major materials sold, 
steel products grew 26.3 percent and coal by 1.3 percent, while 
wood products grew by 26.3 percent. 
  In 1993, the state stepped up price reforms and further 
rationalized the price structure. The value of law played a 
much bigger role. However, because there was an abundant supply 
of commodities and residents became more mature in consumption 
behavior, not to mention prompt government regulation and 
controls, the market operated normally and rises in the 
province's retail prices were much lower than the national 
average. The province's general retail price index and the cost 
of living index for residents were lower their national 
counterparts by 4.8 and 4.3 percentage points respectively. 


